istan Lake ({{convert|1.8|km}} long) that flows through its full length from south to north. The landfill continues for {{convert|3.0|km}} north to Gamache Lake (0.86&nbsp;km), which crosses the stream from south to north for {{convert|0.6|km}}. This last lake has a large central island.\n\nFrom Gamache Lake, the waters flow north for {{convert|1.4|km}} to the outlet of Lamfort Lake. From there, the Malbaie River descends for {{convert|5.7|km}} to Fradette Lake ({{convert|2.5|km}}, oriented to the northeast), which flows through to its full length. Lake Frenette receives by the north-west the waters of lakes Carroll, Milton and Brunette. From the mouth of Fradette Lake, the river flows {{convert|2.4|km}} northeast to Lake Malbaie. The current of the Malbaie River crosses this lake from south to north for {{convert|2.3|km}}.\n\nThe Malbaie Lake outlet is located to the north.\n\n'''Upper course of the Malbaie River downstream of Malbaie Lake''' (segment of {{convert|53.6|km}})\n\n* {{convert|3.6|km}} towards the north by collecting the outlet of Lac Saulmer (coming from the west), then branching east, until the outlet (coming from the north) of a series of lakes including Lac \u00e0 Jack, Lac Fronsac and Petit Lac \u00e0 Jack;\n* {{convert|12.0|km}} towards the north-east by collecting the outlet (coming from the north-west) from the Lac des Sixty-Six, then towards the north, until the confluence of the [[Jardin River]];\n* {{convert|6.0|km}} towards the north by collecting the discharge (coming from the south-east) of Lake Duberger, until the confluence of the [[Hell river]];\n* {{convert|7.7|km}} to the north by collecting the discharge (coming from the west) from Pigeon Lake, then bending towards the northeast at the end of the segment, until the confluence of the [[Petite rivi\u00e8re Malbaie]] (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|6.1|km}} towards the north bending towards the northwest at the end of the segment up to a bend corresponding to the confluence of the [[Chemin des Canots River]] (coming from the south);\n* {{convert|9.1|km}} to the north, forming some coils up to the Barley river (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|9.1|km}} towards the north by collecting the Cold stream (coming from the east) and the Cow's stream (coming from the west), forming a loop towards the northeast and an S , to the confluence of the [[Cruche River (Malbaie River)|Cruche River]] (coming from the west);\n\n'''Intermediate course of the Malbaie river downstream of the Cruche River''' (segment of {{convert|45.1|km}})\n\n* {{convert|0.7|km}} north-east until the confluence of the [[Porc-\u00c9pic River]] (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|6.8|km}} towards the north, forming a large curve towards the east, up to the outlet (coming from the east) of the lake;\n* {{convert|4.1|km}} towards the northwest by collecting the Cran Rouge stream (coming from the south) up to a bend in the river;\n* {{convert|3.4|km}} north-east to Caribou stream (coming from the east);\n* {{convert|6.2|km}} northeasterly to John's Creek (coming from the north);\n* {{convert|6.5|km}} to the east in a deep valley by collecting the discharge (coming from the north) from Lac Plat, then forming a loop towards the south, to a stream (coming from the north) ;\n* {{convert|11.7|km}} towards the east in a deep valley crossing a few rapids at the start of the segment, collecting the North stream (coming from the south) and Scott stream (coming from the north), until at a bend in the river;\n* {{convert|5.7|km}} to the south in a deep valley crossing the \u201cLes Eaux-Mortes\u201d section and a widening of the river, up to the [[rivi\u00e8re des Martres]] (coming from Where is);\n\n'''Lower course of the Malbaie river downstream of the Martres river''' (segment of {{convert|22.9|km}})\n\n* {{convert|2.1|km}} towards the south-east until the Ruisseau des \u00c9rables (coming from the south-west);\n* {{convert|6.8|km}} east to the Larouche stream (from the south), then northeast to the Pont stream (from the northwest);\n* {{convert|4.8|km}} to the east, then south, passing to the east of a mountain, collecting the Cold stream (coming from the west), to the Foulon stream (coming from West);\n* {{convert|2.8|km}} towards the south by forming a loop towards the west at the end of the segment, up to the Rouill\u00e9 stream (coming from the southwest);\n* {{convert|6.4|km}} by forming a {{convert||km}} hook towards the north, then towards the east, the south-east and finally the east, until the brook of the Americans (coming from the north);\n\n'''Lower course of the Malbaie river downstream from the ruisseau des Americans''' (segment of {{convert|30.9|km}})\n\n* {{convert|4.6|km}} to the south, forming a large curve towards the east, collecting the stream of Beavers (coming from the east), up to the stream of Pied des Monts (coming from the Where is);\n* {{convert|10.1|km}} towards the south-east by collecting the outlet (coming from the west) of Long Lake, then towards the northeast by winding, until the outlet of Lake Nairne (coming from South);\n* {{convert|4.3|km}} towards the east by forming a big loop towards the north, until the confluence of the [[Snigole River]] (coming from the northwest) which flows in the middle of a dam lake (length: {{convert|1.9|km}}; altitude: {{convert|59|m}});\n* {{convert|2.0|km}} to the east by crossing a small dam, up to the confluence of the [[Jacob River]] (coming from the north);\n* {{convert|7.4|km}} to the east, forming large loops in the town of [[La Malbaie]], until the confluence of the [[Comport\u00e9 River]] (coming from the north);\n* {{convert|2.5|km}} eastward to its mouth.\n\nThe Malbaie River flows into downtown [[La Malbaie]] on the northwest shore of the [[St. Lawrence River]].\n\n== Toponymy ==\nIn 1608, [[Samuel de Champlain]] named this stream \"Rivi\u00e8re Platte\" or \"Malle Baye\". After the English conquest, the seigneuries of Mount Murray and Murray Bay, so that the English have long named this river ''Murray River''. With time, the Malbaie river finally prevails.<ref name=Toponymie />\n\nChamplain calls the bay \"Malbaie\" in the sense of bad because of the fact that at low tide the latter dries up and the boats run aground. As for \"Murray\", he owes his name to [[James Murray (British Army officer, born 1721)|James Murray]], first governor of [[province of Quebec (1763-1791)|province of Quebec]], which conceded two [[seigneurie]]s at the mouth of the river.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.toponymie.gouv.qc.ca/ct/ToposWeb/fiche.aspx?no_seq=357872|title=La Malbaie|website=Banque de noms de lieux du Qu\u00e9bec|publisher=Commission de toponymie Qu\u00e9bec|access-date=4 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* [[Malbaie Lake (La C\u00f4te-de-Beaupr\u00e9)]]\n* [[La Malbaie]], a municipality\n* [[Laurentides Wildlife Reserve]]\n* [[Grands-Jardins National Park|Grands-Jardins]]\n* [[Hautes-Gorges-de-la-Rivi\u00e8re-Malbaie National Park|Hautes-Gorges-de-la-Rivi\u00e8re-Malbaie]]\n* [[Biosphere Reserve of Charlevoix]]\n* [[Petite rivi\u00e8re Malbaie]]\n* [[St. Lawrence River]]\n* [[List of rivers of Quebec]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:La Malbaie]]\n[[Category:Rivers of Capitale-Nationale]]\n[[Category:Tributaries of the Saint Lawrence River]]\n[[Category:Laurentides Wildlife Reserve]]\n", "name_user": "Veillg1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malbaie_River"}
