:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Break_Up_Song_(Little_Mix_song)"}
{"title_page": "Joseph-Pierre Braemt", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joseph-Pierre Braemt\n| image              = File:Pierre-Joseph Braemt (1864).jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 15 June 1796\n| birth_place        = [[Ghent]]\n| death_date         = 2 December 1864\n| death_place        = [[Brussels]]\n| nationality        = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (KASK)]]<br>[[Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts]]\n| occupation         = [[Medalist]]\n}}\n\n'''Joseph-Pierre Braemt''' (15 June 1796\u20132 December 1864) was a Belgian [[medalist]] and [[coin]] designer.<ref>L. Forrer, Biographical Dictionary of Medallists : Braemt, Joseph Pierre, t. I, London, Spink & Son Ltd, 1904, 691 p., p. 260-261.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nAfter training at the academies of [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (KASK)|Ghent]] and then [[Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts|Brussels]], Joseph-Pierre Braemt perfected his craft in Paris with the engraver Andr\u00e9 Galle and the baron [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Bosio]], a renowned sculptor of the time.\n\nHe was appointed general engraver of the ''H\u00f4tel des Monnaies'' in Brussels and produced the first Belgian coins.\n\n== Works ==\n[[File:Waterloo medal Braemt.jpg|thumb|Waterloo medal by Braemt]]\nHis work includes the following: \n\n*[[1826]] : medal commemorating the completion of the digging of a canal between the Haine and the Escaut, under the government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands,<ref>[http://belgica.kbr.be/fr/coll/med/medK277_6_fr.html M\u00e9daille de Braemt (1826)]</ref>\n*[[1830]] : medal of recognition to the [[Garde Civique|''Garde civique'']], under the [[Provisional Government of Belgium]],\n*Starting in [[1832]] :\n**silver franc coins with the portrait of King Leopold I (5 silver francs, 2 1/2 silver francs, 2 silver francs, 1 silver franc, 1/2 silver franc, 1/4 silver franc, 20 centimes silver),\n**copper pennies with the Belgian lion and the national motto, in French, \"l'union fait la force\" (10 cents, 5 cents, 2 cents and 1 penny).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesfrancs.com/monnaie_belgique.html|title=Monnaie de Belgique|website=www.lesfrancs.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{Commons category|Joseph-Pierre Braemt}}\nA street in the municipality of [[Saint-Josse-ten-Noode]], where he owned a large property called \"Campagne de M. Braemt\" (Mr Braem's countryside), on which the street was partly drawn, bears his name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irismonument.be/fr.Saint-Josse-ten-Noode.Rue_Braemt.html|title=Saint-Josse-ten-Noode - Rue Braemt|website=www.irismonument.be|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* De Seyn, Dictionnaire biographique\u2026., vol. I, sub verbo.\n* L. Forrer, Biographical Dictionary of Medallists : Braemt, Joseph Pierre, t. I, London, Spink & Son Ltd, 1904, 691 p., p. 260-261.\n== References ==\n\n[[Category:Medallists]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Ghent) alumni]]\n[[Category:Coin designers]]\n[[Category:1796 births]]\n[[Category:1864 deaths]]\n<references />\n\n{{Belgium-bio-stub}}\n{{metalworking-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joseph-Pierre Braemt\n| image              = File:Pierre-Joseph Braemt (1864).jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 15 June 1796\n| birth_place        = [[Ghent]]\n| death_date         = 2 December 1864\n| death_place        = [[Brussels]]\n| nationality        = [[Belgium|Belgian]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (KASK)]]<br>[[Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts]]\n| occupation         = [[Medalist]]\n}}\n\n'''Joseph-Pierre Braemt''' (15 June 1796\u20132 December 1864) was a Belgian [[medalist]] and [[coin]] designer.<ref>L. Forrer, Biographical Dictionary of Medallists : Braemt, Joseph Pierre, t. I, London, Spink & Son Ltd, 1904, 691 p., p. 260-261.</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nAfter training at the academies of [[Royal Academy of Fine Arts (KASK)|Ghent]] and then [[Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts|Brussels]], Joseph-Pierre Braemt perfected his craft in Paris with the engraver Andr\u00e9 Galle and the baron [[Fran\u00e7ois Joseph Bosio]], a renowned sculptor of the time.\n\nHe was appointed general engraver of the ''H\u00f4tel des Monnaies'' in Brussels and produced the first Belgian coins.\n\n== Works ==\n[[File:Waterloo medal Braemt.jpg|thumb|Waterloo medal by Braemt]]\nHis work includes the following: \n\n*[[1826]] : medal commemorating the completion of the digging of a canal between the Haine and the Escaut, under the government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands,<ref>[http://belgica.kbr.be/fr/coll/med/medK277_6_fr.html M\u00e9daille de Braemt (1826)]</ref>\n*[[1830]] : medal of recognition to the [[Garde Civique|''Garde civique'']], under the [[Provisional Government of Belgium]],\n*Starting in [[1832]] :\n**silver franc coins with the portrait of King Leopold I (5 silver francs, 2 1/2 silver francs, 2 silver francs, 1 silver franc, 1/2 silver franc, 1/4 silver franc, 20 centimes silver),\n**copper pennies with the Belgian lion and the national motto, in French, \"l'union fait la force\" (10 cents, 5 cents, 2 cents and 1 penny).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesfrancs.com/monnaie_belgique.html|title=Monnaie de Belgique|website=www.lesfrancs.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{Commons category|Joseph-Pierre Braemt}}\nA street in the municipality of [[Saint-Josse-ten-Noode]], where he owned a large property called \"Campagne de M. Braemt\" (Mr Braem's countryside), on which the street was partly drawn, bears his name.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irismonument.be/fr.Saint-Josse-ten-Noode.Rue_Braemt.html|title=Saint-Josse-ten-Noode - Rue Braemt|website=www.irismonument.be|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* De Seyn, Dictionnaire biographique\u2026., vol. I, sub verbo.\n* L. Forrer, Biographical Dictionary of Medallists : Braemt, Joseph Pierre, t. I, London, Spink & Son Ltd, 1904, 691 p., p. 260-261.\n== References ==\n\n[[Category:Medallists]]\n[[Category:Acad\u00e9mie Royale des Beaux-Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Royal Academy of Fine Arts (Ghent) alumni]]\n[[Category:Coin designers]]\n[[Category:1796 births]]\n[[Category:1864 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-bio-stub}}\n{{metalworking-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Brookford", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph-Pierre_Braemt"}
